<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910828-0019</DOCNO><DOCID>910828-0019.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- McDermott International Inc.:   `Positive' Settlement Expected   From Sinking of Derrick Barge</HL><DATE>08/28/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><CO>   MDR</CO><MS>ENERGY (ENE)</MS><IN>OIL EQUIPMENT, SERVICES, PLATFORM SUPPLIERS (EQS)OIL-EQUIPMENT AND SERVICES (OIE)PETROLEUM (PET)</IN><NS>PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)</NS><RE>LOUISIANA (LA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   McDermott International Inc.'s derrick barge disasterearlier this month should result in a &quot;positive financialeffect&quot; after settlement with insurers, a company officialsaid.   At the time of the accident, in which 22 people werekilled, the barge was being towed out of the way of a typhoonin the South China Sea. &quot;The typoon changed direction andovertook the barge,&quot; George Stoddart, a McDermott vicepresident, said. &quot;Beyond that we don't have any moreinformation.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   Of the 195 people on board at the time of the accident,173 survived, Mr. Stoddart said. The bodies of 16 people havebeen recovered. Six are missing and presumed dead.   Mr. Stoddart said McDermott, an energy services company,formed a team to investigate events leading to the Aug. 15capsizing and sinking of the barge.   The executive said the barge, in 200 feet of water, &quot;ismost probably a total loss.&quot; He said McDermott is fullycovered by insurance. He wouldn't be more specific except tosay that upon settlement the company expects to have a smallfinancial gain.</TEXT></DOC>